<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>MULTI-LINK FRONT AIR SUSPENSION - CHECKS AND ADJUSTMENTS - RIDE HEIGHT</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="c01" svcproctype="Checks and Adjustments" graphiccount="4">
        <title>RIDE HEIGHT</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Checking Ride Height</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Park the vehicle unloaded on a level surface.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Chock wheels to prevent vehicle movement.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Release the parking brake.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Let the air pressure build to governor cut-out pressure, which should occur between 115
                    and 130 psi (793 and 896 kPa), and shut off the engine.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0301507" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/G0301507.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Exhaust Air</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. HEIGHT CONTROL ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. BOLT AND WASHER</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. VALVE LEVER</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The multi-link front air suspension is equipped with a ride height control valve on each side.
                        Be sure to perform steps 5 through 8 on both sides of the multi-link front air suspension.
                    </para>
                </note>
                <important>
                    <para>It is very important that the height control valve be cycled completely before and after any
                        ride height adjustments. Cycling of the height control valve will help make the adjustment more
                        accurate.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove bolt, washer, nut, and height control rod from the valve lever.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0301519" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/G0301519.webp" type="webp" scalefitwidth="312px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Dump Air</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. FILL POSITION</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. EXHAUST POSITION</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. VALVE LEVER</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dump air from air spring by rotating the valve lever to the EXH (exhaust) position.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect the height control rod to the valve lever with the bolt, washer, and nut. Torque
                    bolt to 60 to 80 lbf-in (7 to 9 N&#8226;m). Allow the suspension to fill to ride height.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0301522" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/G0301522.webp" type="webp" scalefitwidth="312px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Ride Height Measurement</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HEIGHT TOOL</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. LEADING EDGE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. AIR SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. LOWER FLANGE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure the ride height at the air spring. Special tool number
                    <emph type="bold">3822154C1</emph>
                    is recommended to measure the air spring ride height.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The measurement you obtain should fall within the
                    <emph type="bold">Target Air Spring Height</emph>
                    shown in the
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t1">Ride Height Specifications</hotlnk>
                    table. If the measurement does not fall within the value shown on the table, the height control
                    valve will need to be adjusted.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Ride Height Adjustment</title>
            <figure id="f0301524" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg03/G0301524.webp" type="webp" scalefitwidth="312px" scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Ride Height Adjustment</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. VALVE LEVER</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. VALVE LEVER SCREW</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not loosen valve lever screw so far as to disengage the valve lever from the ride height
                        valve.
                    </para>
                </caution>
                <important>
                    <para>It is very important that the height control valve be cycled completely before and after any
                        ride height adjustments. Cycling of the height control valve will help make the adjustment more
                        accurate.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It is required that the system be brought to proper ride height by filling the system using
                        the ride height control valve, not by exhausting the system to proper ride height.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Adjust the ride height by performing the following steps:</para>
                <seqlist style="arabic">
                    <item>
                        <para>Fill system to desired ride height.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Loosen the valve lever screw.</para>
                        <seqlist>
                            <item>
                                <para>Push or pull on the pivot point of the valve lever to adjust.</para>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <para>Adjustment is provided by the slot at the valve lever screw.</para>
                            </item>
                        </seqlist>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Rotate the valve lever to fill with air until the correct ride height is attained. Only
                            adjust to proper ride height by filling with air. If ride height is higher than correct ride
                            height, exhaust enough air to lower ride height below proper ride height, and refill
                            accordingly.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Torque the valve lever screw to 50 to 55 lbf-in (6 N&#8226;m).</para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the ride height measurement by dropping the suspension and allowing the height
                    control valve to air up to ride height.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Recheck the ride height adjustment.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
